metadata.name: Dencity #696
metadata.description:
Dencity is a generative art project inspired by aerial views of cities with a high density of buildings. Its perspective effect, its perfectly imprecise lines, its subtle textures and its very advanced level of detail give it the appearance of a hand-drawn work.

Behind the visible art (the image) hides another form of art, an extremely complex algorithm capable of calculating and drawing in 2D each variation of the Dencity project. To draw a variation, the algorithm notably takes around 3,000,000 to 20,000,000 random decisions based on the hash of the mint and draws around 800,000 to 4,000,000 lines to create all the strokes and texture effects.

Made with ❤️, code and p5js.

metadata.name: Wish You Were Here #42
metadata.description:
This artwork was created while experimenting with noise fields and it instantly evoked a feeling of nostalgia in me. It's coded entirely in p5.js and renders domain warped flow fields on a paper canvas-like texture.

Please note that it takes about 5-10 seconds for the artwork to start loading. And it’s best viewed on a screen bigger than a mobile phone, while listening to this track called ‘Wish You Were Here' by Pink Floyd: 
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hjpF8ukSrvk

Artwork loads at 1000px by 1000px resolution by default. Press ‘2’,’4’ or ‘8’ to load as 2000px by 2000px, 4000px by 4000px or 8000px by 8000px respectively.
Press 's' at any time to download the rendered resolution.

metadata.name: ASCII-SCAPE #221
metadata.description:
ASCII-SCAPE

Like for many others growing up during the 1980s & 90s, my very first hands-on encounter with actual computer graphics (outside of games) was in the form of "textmode" and its various alphanumeric characters and other symbols available on the 8bit home computers of that period. These machines were perfectly capable of producing fairly high-resolution & multi-color graphics (all relative), yet most systems booted into an interactive prompt with the so-called textmode as de-facto standard environment, providing a level, if also limited, playing field for the creation of text-based graphics from a patchwork of characters & symbols of a predefined font (system or custom). As is so often the case, limitation is the mother of invention and the regular, monospaced grid and standardized set of characters quickly encouraged an entire subculture of specialized designers & artists to emerge (which is currently being re-discovered & remixed by younger generations), applying & showcasing their creativity (with often surprisingly ingenious skills) in the form of game designs, user interfaces, disk mags, demoscene productions, competitions, flyers, BBSes and even various early Web designs of the mid/late 90s.

ASCII-SCAPE is an attempted non-nostalgic homage to these roots & culture. It is also a textmode-only (no canvas!) rework of my previous piece C-SCAPE. It combines my love of cellular automata with the stripped back aesthetics & limitations of using only text as representation medium of these co-evolving generative systems. It required an almost complete rewrite & re-curation of various elements: 1200+ new handpicked rule combinations, 32 character sets, 40 color themes, new relationships & biases to better manage the resulting textures, densities and contrast.

Although technically not strictly "ASCII" (an actual standard, but also a popular shorthand for "text only"), the entire simulation only uses various Unicode characters and the beautiful Iosevka open source typeface by Renzhi Li aka Belleve Invis.

Like its parent C-SCAPE, this project is dynamic and evolves indefinitely. It's best viewed on non-mobile devices, where there's a decent horizontal resolution to provide sufficient simulation space. Please see the C-SCAPE project description for further details. There's no graphical export feature, but output can be captured into an UTF-8 plain text file (max. 100k lines/generations).

The following keyboard shortcuts are available:

- space : toggle simulation updates (pause/play)
- r : randomize environment
- x : start/stop recording
- f : toggle scroll speed (fast/slow)

metadata.name: Frames #13
metadata.description:
Everyone has a different life narrative to share, and one particular incident can make all the difference in the world in how your life differs from everyone else's. We undoubtedly experience an unfathomable number of events during our lives, and the culmination of these situations has shaped who we are today. Yet, we only remember some of them. Each situation is entangled in the memory of our senses related to the events that occurred in that situation. Separately, events that we recall make the whole picture of our life inside a frame full of successions and intersections of scenes pictured within a limitless number of frames, each one presenting an event that we live. That's what makes our life a puzzle; you can only see the picture when you put all the pieces together. 

Press [s] to save captured image to png (6540px X 7704)

Wait a moment it takes a while to be rendered
---
Created using vanilla javascript
KrouniHatim - Nov22
---
(CC BY-ND 4.0)

metadata.name: Chaotic Attraction #11
metadata.description:
The world shifts into chaos, which we then attempt to correct. Chaos is the world's natural state. Similar to how a strong emote slowly defends itself until a new one "corrects" its direction. Simply put, this is entropy as defined by thermodynamics.
Order is free will; chaos is fate. We are all drawn to fate in some way, that instinctive desire to watch a fire burn. Every single one of us is just as wired for order as for chaos.
Maintaining order requires work, sacrifice, and effort. The beauty of letting go of inhibitions and returning to our more primal fascination is intoxicating in chaos where we only need to exist.

And that almost acts as our adrenaline, reflecting on everyone. A chaotic environment might energize them, release all those feel-good brain chemicals, and actually make them feel good.
Another thing to consider is that most creative work is chaotic and random, and most artists intentionally introduce chaos or randomness into their work in order to find fresh "opportunities" and rekindle their creativity. You must constantly use new colors if you want to keep the world colorful. A world of white and black can be creative; a world of blue and red cannot. Using the same colors repeatedly in a "imitative" manner will only kill it.
Chaos gives life more color, possibilities, chances, and opportunities, and it's full of pleasant and unpleasant surprises. People have become so dumb and lazy that they are no longer able to make the best of both bad and positive circumstances and events.

Wait a moment it takes a while to be rendered

metadata.name: Neural Collapse #130
metadata.description:
What happens when your brain overloads, or when you lose control of your giant robot.

A study on the repetition and stacking of a simple but very dynamic structure.

Everything procedurally generated at runtime.
You can find more informations on the piece, its design and origins, here: https://ulucode.com/wp/neural-collapse/

Interactivity : 
- You can hover your mouse on the connectors to close them... temporarily
- Press and hold the mouse button to slightly move the viewpoint.

- Press "a" to increase quality of the antialiasing (3 levels), at the cost of performances. Especially useful on the palettes using outlines.
- Export a PNG capture at various resolutions by pressing the number keys 1 to 9 (top row or numpad, and only in live mode, after pressing "open"). Resolutions ranges from 720 to 7680 pixels. I recommend starting with "4".

GPU recommended. Best performances on Chrome in general.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: NEW TERRITORIES #86
metadata.description:
On desktop, open project in live view
Rotate and zoom with the mouse to explore the model
Click “S” to download STL 3D model file
Click “P” to download PNG file (3600x3600)


New Territories

New Territories is the sequel to Cityblocks. In this series, urban ensembles are generated with a simple click. With each iteration appears a new densely built city block. Graced with impeccable geometrical lines, devoid of any human presence, these buildings remind us of brutalist utopias like Le Corbusier’s Cité radieuse or Niemeyer’s Brasilia. But despite their clearly modernist feel, there is something hauntingly primitive about them. They could be either New Mexican adobe pueblos, Minoan palaces, or Turkish troglodyte dwellings. Both carved and sculpted, these Ghormenghasts of concrete float in a realm out of time, like in some architect’s dream.

The purpose of this creative work is to generate 3D architectural projects that could be implemented in the real world. The accelerating lives that we live, complicated by growing and unpredictable environmental crises, call for an enhanced capacity to come up quickly with new architectural solutions adapted to different contexts. From computer assisted design to 3D printing, from augmented reality to real-life housing, from sculpture to architecture, this work aims at bridging the gap between the virtual and the tangible.

Working as a visual artist, David Umemoto draws inspiration from his training as an architect. He has been using low-tech methods for a long time, refining his talent for elegant simple shapes and combinatory constructions. Now, poured concrete and home-made moulds are giving way to zero-gravity rotating models. The skills he developed while working with real objects find a new playground in the virtual realm.

metadata.name: CryptoPixels #812
metadata.description:
The ultimate collectible.
 
Traits? Well, each pixel has an R value, a G value, and a B value. And yeah, Tyler Hobbs, we know you’re reading and are about to say we should use H, S, and B instead but you can shove it up your ass right along with your Fidenza billions. Real deep up there.
 
Utility? With only 576 CryptoPixels you can make a CryptoPunk worth millions!
 
Rarity? Each pixel is provably unique (in the Heraclitean sense). And you know how one of your drunk crypto bros mentioned hashes once and it was the only word short enough for you to remember after blacking out? We give you 3 hashes. Think of the street cred with the even dumber fuckers out there buying random numbers!
 
Bullshit hidden messages? Oh yeah, you’re getting excited now, aren’t you? We’ve done some real alien shit and buried blueprints for a spaceship in here. You just have to work with the “community” to combine your pixels into the plans. Real. Fucking. Interstellar. Travel. How’s that roadmap?
 
Is this art? Are you art?

metadata.description:
Personally, I enjoy arranging and combining unusual elements together.
In this collection, you can have both normal and unusual combinations of unrelated objects, yet very eye-catching and harmonious.
Which item do you prefer?
Although, it depends on your luck which combination you get.

If you find one of the gun in hand and and a black dress with a gun blank , in addition to a Super Rare edition, there are also prize
for the owners in the Primary market, which are as follows:
The lucky winners will get 2 Morixels Dog NFT

The Nexi is unique random Generated 200 PFP NFTs. The number of Traits in this collection is 6 (30 layers) and it has the ability to make unique 15,000 NFTs.

To create balance, these NFTs are randomly minted, and this is a chance for everyone to get a rare version. So due to the low price of these NFTs, if the rare version did not belong to you, it is still possible for you to mint the new NFTs.

Because this is an NFT in PFP format, you can put it on your avatar on Twitter or Instagram.

This project is a collaboration project and it is a Benefit for the owners of the most Morixels Mans to Collaborate with Morixels Designer.

You can read more information on Morixels website 👇

Website: https://morixels.com/

Twitter: @Morixels

by: @morteza_yousefy & @negar_khozhandi

metadata.name: Slumbers #259
metadata.description:
Generative abstract artwork that explores forms, shapes, coloring and brushwork.

Options:

- press 'f' to turn off paper-like texture (recommended for print on hi-quality paper)
- press 's' to save the PNG image of the current view
- press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to save hi-res PNG images

Colors and textures might differ slightly on some devices due to the heavy use of low alpha blending. Calibrated and tested on Firefox 107.0 & Chrome 107.0.5304.107 on Win10 x64 Intel machine.

Created using p5js.

@VolatileMoods, November, 2022.
